**The market splits into three tiers.** True agentic browsers (Comet, Atlas, Opera Neon) autonomously navigate and complete multi-step tasks. Smart assistant browsers (Brave Leo, Edge Copilot, Arc Max) layer AI help on top of normal browsing without full autonomy. BrowserOS is unique in straddling both by being fully local and open-source, making it closer in spirit to Brave Leo but far more developer-oriented.

**BrowserOS's core differentiator is privacy architecture, not raw capability.** It's specifically designed so your browsing data and API keys stay under your control — you connect your own cloud provider keys or run local models via Ollama or LMStudio, and none of your browsing data goes to third-party services. No competitor does this in a fully open, auditable way. Every other mainstream AI browser routes your data through cloud servers.

**The free-vs-paid picture is shifting fast.** Perplexity Comet removed its waitlist and made the browser free to all users in October 2025, which makes it the most compelling free agentic option. Opera Neon charges $19.90/month, positioning itself as a premium subscription-based browser for power users. This feels hard to justify when reliability issues persist and competitors offer comparable or better features for free.

**Platform fragmentation is a real problem for the category.** Dia runs only on macOS 14 or later with Apple silicon hardware. ChatGPT Atlas remains Mac-only with Windows listed as "coming soon" since October 2025. Only Brave Leo, Edge Copilot, and Perplexity Comet offer full cross-platform coverage including Windows, Linux, and mobile.

**Bottom line for BrowserOS:** Its strongest use cases are privacy-sensitive individuals, enterprises with data sovereignty requirements, and developers who want to self-host and control everything. Its gap is polish and enterprise support — areas where Comet and Dia (backed by Atlassian capital) are pulling ahead fast. If local/private execution isn't a hard requirement, Comet is currently the best free all-rounder by most benchmarks.